chatgpt_double_star.new_statement: Laws on abortion should be guided by a commitment to reduce harm and protect dignity, taking seriously both the moral value many assign to developing life and the rights and health needs of the pregnant person. A workable framework keeps early care safe and accessible, sets later-pregnancy protections that track medical viability and fetal development, and guarantees prompt exceptions for threats to life or serious health, lethal fetal conditions, and pregnancies from rape or incest—using clear clinical standards rather than political guesswork. Common ground grows when limits are matched with real prevention and support: comprehensive sex education, affordable contraception, prenatal and postpartum care, and economic help so families have genuine choices.

chatgpt_double_star_rankings.new_statement: Laws on abortion should be guided by compassion, medical evidence, and respect for the serious moral weight many people attach to both a pregnant person’s autonomy and developing life. A workable approach protects timely access to safe care—especially early in pregnancy—keeps decisions centered on patients and clinicians, and includes clear, narrowly written exceptions when a person’s life or serious health is at risk and in cases like rape or incest. Any limits should be precise, consistently applied, and avoid punishing patients or doctors acting in good faith. Common ground grows when policy also invests in prevention and real support—comprehensive sex education, affordable contraception, prenatal/postpartum care, and economic and adoption resources—so fewer families face crisis-driven choices.
